File Handling in C++

C++ provides file handling through the <fstream> library. There are three main classes:

ifstream â€“ Input file stream (used to read from files)

ofstream â€“ Output file stream (used to write to files)

fstream â€“ File stream (used for both reading and writing)

File Open Modes

You can specify how the file should be opened using modes:

ios::in â€“ Open file for reading (default for ifstream)

ios::out â€“ Open file for writing (default for ofstream)

ios::app â€“ Append data to the end of the file

ios::ate â€“ Open file and move pointer to the end

ios::trunc â€“ Truncate the file to 0 length (default for ofstream)

ios::binary â€“ Open file in binary mode instead of text

Example:

ofstream file("example.txt", ios::out | ios::app);


Opens example.txt for writing and appends data to the end.

Important File Functions

Opening a file

ifstream inFile("data.txt");   // Open file for reading
ofstream outFile("output.txt"); // Open file for writing


Closing a file

inFile.close();
outFile.close();


Reading from a file

getline() â€“ Reads one line at a time

string line;
getline(inFile, line);


>> operator â€“ Reads formatted input (like cin)

int num;
inFile >> num;


Writing to a file

<< operator â€“ Write formatted output

outFile << "Hello, World!" << endl;


Checking file status

is_open() â€“ Checks if the file is successfully opened

if (!inFile.is_open()) {
    cout << "Failed to open file" << endl;
}


eof() â€“ Checks if end of file is reached

while (!inFile.eof()) {
    getline(inFile, line);
}


fail() â€“ Checks if file operation failed

if (inFile.fail()) {
    cout << "Error reading file" << endl;
}


Binary file functions

read() â€“ Reads raw bytes

char buffer[100];
inFile.read(buffer, sizeof(buffer));


write() â€“ Writes raw bytes

outFile.write(buffer, sizeof(buffer));


Seeking in a file

seekg() â€“ Move read pointer (input)

seekp() â€“ Move write pointer (output)

tellg() / tellp() â€“ Get current pointer position

inFile.seekg(0, ios::beg);   // Move to beginning
outFile.seekp(0, ios::end);  // Move to end

