Exercise: Find Maximum in a 2D Array

Objective:
Write a function that finds the maximum value in a 3x3 matrix entered by the user.

Instructions

Create a 3x3 matrix (two-dimensional array).

Write a function findMax that iterates through the matrix and returns the largest element.

Display the maximum element.

Example

Input:

3 5 2
8 6 1
4 7 9


Output:

The maximum element is: 9

C++ Solution
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Function to find the maximum element in a 3x3 matrix
int findMax(int matrix[3][3]) {
    int maxVal = matrix[0][0];
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            if (matrix[i][j] > maxVal)
                maxVal = matrix[i][j];
        }
    }
    return maxVal;
}

int main() {
    int matrix[3][3];

    cout << "Enter elements of the 3x3 matrix:" << endl;
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++)
            cin >> matrix[i][j];

    cout << "The maximum element is: " << findMax(matrix) << endl;

    return 0;
}

How It Works

findMax function:

Starts with the first element as the maximum.

Loops through all elements to check if any value is greater.

Updates maxVal if a larger number is found.

Main function:

Reads a 3x3 matrix from the user.

Calls findMax and prints the result.

Exercise: Display Distinct Numbers

Objective:
Write a program that reads 10 non-zero integers from the user and displays only the distinct numbers.
Numbers that appear multiple times should only appear once in the output.

Instructions

Read 10 non-zero integer numbers from the user.

Check if the number has already been entered:

If yes â†’ discard it

If no â†’ store it in an array

After reading all numbers, display only the distinct numbers.

Example

Input:

1 2 3 4 -1 4 4 3 8 10


Output:

The distinct numbers are: 1 2 3 4 -1 8 10

C++ Solution
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

const int SIZE = 10;

// Function to check if a number already exists in the array
bool isNumberInList(int numbers[], int number) {
    for (int i = 0; i < SIZE; i++) {
        if (number == numbers[i])
            return true;
    }
    return false;
}

int main() {
    int numbers[SIZE] = {}; // array to store distinct numbers
    int number, count = 0;

    cout << "Enter ten numbers: ";

    for (int i = 0; i < SIZE; i++) {
        cin >> number;

        // Skip the number if it already exists in the array
        if (isNumberInList(numbers, number))
            continue;
        else {
            numbers[count] = number;
            count++;
        }
    }

    // Display distinct numbers
    cout << "The distinct numbers are: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < SIZE; i++) {
        if (numbers[i] == 0)
            break;
        cout << numbers[i] << " ";
    }
    cout << endl;

    return 0;
}

How It Works

isNumberInList function: Checks if a number already exists in the array.

Main loop: Reads 10 numbers and stores only the new numbers.

Output loop: Prints the numbers until a 0 is found (unused array positions remain 0).

